The multi-agent debate is the central reasoning engine of the pipeline involving five adjudication roles—Plaintiff Counsel, Defense Counsel, and three Judges—each assigned to a different underlying model (Table 2 ). Heterogeneous assignment serves to prevent collusion from shared representations, introduce authentic disagreement, and improve argument diversity across rounds, as homogeneous agents cannot reliably improve over majority vote, while diversity in agent capabilities is critical for effective deliberation (Zhang et al. , 2026 ; Zhu et al. , 2026 ) .

Each debate round executes five steps: (1) Evidence discovery: Both agents independently identify an evidential gap and propose a targeted query, which the Judge refines before execution via P-RAG, with novel results admitted to the shared pool. (2) Argument generation: Each agent produces a structured legal argument grounded in the current evidence pool and debate history. (3) Expert witness testimony: Either side may request a domain expert; if granted by the Judge, a domain-specific persona is dynamically generated to provide targeted testimony. This mechanism enables access to specialized knowledge without predefining expert domains. (4) Self-reflection: Each agent critiques its own performance, with identified gaps injected into the next round’s P-RAG query (Section 2.6 ). (5) Critic evaluation: The Critic Agent independently scores both sides and signals early termination if all key premises have been addressed.

The debate runs for up to max_rounds = 10 =10 but terminates early when any of the
following conditions are met:
(i) Reflection plateau: | Δ ​ total_reflection_score | < 0.05 |\Delta\,\texttt{total\_reflection\_score}|<0.05 for two
consecutive rounds;
(ii) Critic resolution: debate_resolved=True ;
(iii) Novelty exhaustion: average novelty < 0.10 <0.10 over two consecutive P-RAG calls;
or (iv) Judicial signal: the Court agent affirms readiness to deliberate.

Agent: DeepSeek-R1 ( openrouter ) System Prompt: You are the Independent Critic Agent. Your role is to evaluate the
debate rounds for logical coherence, evidence coverage, and rebuttal
quality. Round Evaluation Prompt: You are the Critic Agent observing a courtroom-style scientific debate. Claim: {claim} Round: {round_num} Recent Proceedings: {history_summary} Analyze both the Plaintiff and Defense Counsel’s performance in this round. Score each side (0.0 to 1.0) on: 1. Logical Coherence: Argument flow and structure. 2. Evidence Coverage: How well they used admitted exhibits. 3. Rebuttal Coverage: Did they address the opponent’s strongest points? Identify any premises that remain "unresolved" or under-supported. Provide actionable recommendations for both sides to improve their discovery and arguments. Respond ONLY in valid JSON format: {
    "plaintiff": {
        "logic": 0.0,
        "evidence": 0.0,
        "rebuttal": 0.0,
        "reasoning": "..."
    },
    "defense": {
        "logic": 0.0,
        "evidence": 0.0,
        "rebuttal": 0.0,
        "reasoning": "..."
    },
    "unresolved_premises": ["...", "..."],
    "recommendations": {
        "plaintiff": ["...", "..."],
        "defense": ["...", "..."],
        "queries": ["suggested search query 1", "..."]
    },
    "debate_resolved": false
}
